@NODE INTRODUCTION "NetDOCK-2 Help Document: Introduction"
 ---------------==========++++* @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Introduction@{FG TEXT} *++++==========---------------

 In 1999, Gareth Griffiths perfected the original release of NetDOCK, the
 definitive Internet Dockbar. Unfortunately, due to a bad hard-drive crash
 whilst he was backing-up all the data on his hard drive, he lost
 everything. Rather ironic really. As a result, he lost both the source
 code and the archives to NetDOCK.

 So, he decided to start again. He originally planned to just write NetDOCK
 again in exactly the same form as he had done before. It was then that he
 realised that the original didn't offer the level of configurability that
 he originally set out to achieve. In an attempt to rectify this, he began
 work on NetDOCK v2. In the early beta stages (the last beta being v0.97)
 there were many problems with the code, it was both sloppy, and also non-
 efficient, and used up too much valuable CPU time.

 After two months of TOTAL re-coding, and a few days of minor tweaking
 shoved on to the end, the final NetDOCK-2 is here! It is now accompanied
 by it's very own Preferences Program - ND2-Prefs. Similar to the original 
 NetDOCK's settings program, PathPrefs, ND2-Prefs is very easy to use.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHAREWARE "NetDOCK-2 Help Document: SHAREWARE!"
 ---------------==========+++++* @{FG HIGHLIGHT}SHAREWARE!@{FG TEXT} *+++++==========---------------

 You must appreciate the amount of effort that went into the production of
 NetDOCK-2. If you use this program a lot, then you should show that 
 appreciation by donating a small sum of money (Ł5!) to the author.

 To acquire the registered version of the program costs you nothing, you
 have it on your hard drive right now! However, you can still donate Ł5 to
 me if you really want to! ;) To do this, just send either a British cheque,
 postal order, or British cash through the post to my address, which I will
 be more than pleased to give you if you e-mail me asking for it. 

 Paying by Cash is preferable. To do this, simply sandwich your banknotes
 in between two pieces of paper to avoid it being seen, and send it to the
 address below.

 To get my address, simply e-mail me asking for it at this address:

                        mail@gazchap.btinternet.co.uk
@ENDNODE
@NODE SYSREQ "NetDOCK-2 Help Document: System Requirements"
 ---------------=========+++*@{FG HIGHLIGHT} System Requirements @{FG TEXT}*+++=========---------------

 NetDOCK-2 should be usable on most Amiga systems. The main executable
 itself (ie. the file labelled NetDOCK-2) does not use any OS2.0+ specific
 commands, so should work on any Workbench 1.3 system. Whether it will work
 on a Workbench 1.2 system is unknown. I wouldn't have thought many people
 still use that though anyway!

 Here's the full list of requirements for the two executables:

 @{FG HIGHLIGHT}NetDOCK-2@{FG TEXT}
   · An Amiga equipped with Kickstart/Workbench 1.3 or above.
   · Around 100K free RAM, excluding image files.
   · A mouse.
   
 @{FG HIGHLIGHT}ND2-Prefs@{FG TEXT}
   · An Amiga equipped with Kickstart/Workbench 2.04 or above.
   · Around 80K free RAM, excluding settings buffers.
   · A mouse.
   · A storage medium for the settings, preferably a Hard Drive.

 NetDOCK-2 in it's entirety functions best on a Hard Drive. The program has
 been tested on these systems:
 
   · A1200/020, KS/WB3.0, 2mb Chip, 8mb Fast, HD, CD-ROM. 
   · A1200/020, KS/WB3.0, 2mb Chip, 0mb Fast, HD.
	· A1200/060, KS3.1/WB3.5, 2mb Chip, 16mb Fast, HD, CD-ROM.

 If NetDOCK-2 functions perfectly on your system (ie. there are no sudden
 crashes) then please let me know your system setup. 

 Compatibility with graphics cards is not certain, if you find NetDOCK-2 
 doesn't work on your system, whether it is fitted with a graphics card or
 not, then please let me know, so I can either try and stamp out the
 conflicting routines, or notify people in these docs.

 24-bit icons are not supported, so that pretty much says graphics cards are
 not 100% supported :-(

@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALLATION "NetDOCK-2 Help Document: Installation"
 ---------------==========++++++*@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Installation @{FG TEXT}*+++++==========---------------

 To install NetDOCK-2 manually, simply copy the NetDOCK-2 directory to a
 place on your hard drive and add the following line to your S:User-Startup
 file:

                        Assign NetDOCK2: xxx:xxxxxxxxxxxx

 Where xxx: is the device name, eg. DH1: or Work: and xxxxxxxxxxxx is the
 directory structure to the NetDOCK-2 folder, eg. Utils/NetDOCK-2.

 Using the above examples, the line would look like this:

                       Assign NetDOCK2: DH1:Utils/NetDOCK-2

 If you are having problems installing the program, then write to me
 explaining your problem.
@ENDNODE
@NODE USING-ND2 "NetDOCK-2 Help Document: Using NetDOCK-2"
 ---------------==========++++*@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Using NetDOCK-2 @{FG TEXT}*++++==========---------------

 @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Loading the program.@{FG TEXT}

 Firstly, to start NetDOCK-2 from Workbench, simply double-click on it's
 icon. To start it from the CLI/Shell, use the CD command to CD into the
 NetDOCK-2 directory, and then type NetDOCK-2.

 After doing this, a small window should appear, saying 'Loading images...'
 and then a number, decreasing down to 0. When it reaches 0, the toolbar
 will appear. If one of the images could not be loaded, you will be
 notified and the program will exit.

 The Toolbar looks like this:

 +-+---------------------------------------------------+-+-+
 |O| <Title set in prefs> (Program Mode)               |O|O|
 +-+---------------------------------------------------+-+-+
 |                                                         |
 |   The icons appear here.                                |
 |                                                         |
 |                                                         |
 +---------------------------------------------------------+

 @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Running programs.@{FG TEXT}

 To run a program, simply click on it's icon. The program specified in the
 prefs will execute, and you can carry on as normal.

 If you find that your icons are not very descriptive, and you don't know
 what program a certain icon is linked to, then press the HELP key. The
 (Program Mode) in the titlebar should change to (Help Mode). Now, clicking
 on an icon brings up a requester telling you the Program Name, the
 executable it is linked to, and the image file that is set for it. Click
 OK to exit this requester.

 To leave Help Mode and return to Program Mode, simply press HELP again on
 your keyboard. The titlebar text should change from (Help Mode) back to
 (Program Mode) and the function of the icons is as normal.

 @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Menus.@{FG TEXT}

 NetDOCK-2 comes with a standard menu. Hold down the right mouse button
 whilst the NetDOCK-2 toolbar is active and it will appear. The menu
 functions are as follows.

   NetDOCK-2 Settings: Calls ND2-Prefs from within the main program. Also
                       enables notification, ie. the new preferences will
                       be auto-loaded on exit from ND2-Prefs.

   Snapshot Window:    Snapshots the window position where it currently is.
                       Means the window will reappear there when started up
                       again. Note that some screen positions render the 
                       toolbar unable to render, so it defaults to 0,14 if
                       that happens.

   Help:               Calls up this document.

   About NetDOCK-2:    Displays the About Box, displaying registration
                       information etc.

   Quit:               I am sure you won't use this! But if you do, it
                       exits the program.

 And that is pretty much all there is to using the NetDOCK-2 program. The
 ND2-Prefs program is a different kettle of fish however!
@ENDNODE
@NODE USING-ND2P "NetDOCK-2 Help Document: Using ND2-Prefs"
 ---------------==========++++*@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Using ND2-Prefs @{FG TEXT}*++++==========---------------

 @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Loading the ND2-Prefs program.@{FG TEXT}

 This can be done three ways:

  · From Workbench. Double Click on the ND2-Prefs icon.

  · From CLI/Shell. CD to the NetDOCK-2 directory and type ND2-Prefs.

  · From NetDOCK-2 itself. Select NetDOCK-2 Settings from the menu in 
    NetDOCK-2. (registered users only).

 Once it has been started, the settings will load, and the GUI will appear.
 It consists of a few string gadgets, a couple of slider bars and a few
 buttons. Here's the lowdown on ALL of them.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Dockbar Title:@{FG TEXT} Sets the text to be displayed in
                 the titlebar of the toolbar. Default: Internet Dockbar.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}No of Icons:@{FG TEXT} Sets the number of icons on the
               toolbar. Max. of 99 (or 5 in the unregistered version).

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Selected Image:@{FG TEXT} Sets the image file to be 
                  displayed when you click on an icon. Type in a path to the
                  file here, or use the adjacent 'L' button to select a file
                  from the file requester. STANDARD IFF BRUSHES ONLY!

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Icon:@{FG TEXT} Sets the icon to be modified. Has a
        maximum value of whatever 'No of Icons' is set to. Settings
        for a certain icon automatically change as you select
        another icon.
  
  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Program Name:@{FG TEXT} Enter a name for the Program here.
                This is what the program will be referred to as in Help
                Mode. EG, Miami or AmiTCP.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Path:@{FG TEXT} Sets the path to the executable. Type in a
        path to the file, or click on the adjacent 'L' button to 
        select one from the file requester. Scripts should be 
        accepted, but this is not confirmed.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Image:@{FG TEXT} Sets the image for the icon. Type in a
         path to the image file, or click on the adjacent 'L' button to
         select one from the file requester. IFF BRUSHES ONLY!

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Save:@{FG TEXT} Saves all the current settings to disk. If
        you have run ND2-Prefs from within NetDOCK-2, the new settings will 
        be automatically loaded in upon exit of ND2-Prefs.

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Cancel:@{FG TEXT} Abandons all changes, and exits the ND2-Prefs program.

 Editing all the settings using the GUI can be quite tedious, especially if
 you have got 99 icons on the one toolbar! That is why it is also possible
 to edit the settings manually using a text editor.
 Read @{"Configuration Format" LINK CFGFORMAT} for details on this.
@ENDNODE 
@NODE CFGFORMAT "NetDOCK-2 Help Document: Configuration Format"
 --------------=========+++* @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Configuration Format@{FG TEXT} *+++==========--------------

 Because editing settings using ND2-Prefs can sometimes be very tedious, I
 have purposefully allowed you to edit settings manually. There are three
 settings files, and only two really need modification. They are stored in
 the Settings directory inside the NetDOCK-2 folder. There are three files
 inside:

     general                        program                    window

 The first two are the ones which need changing. The configuration format
 for these two files is as follows:
 
  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}general@{FG TEXT}

      1. DOCKBAR TITLE
      2. NUMBER OF ICONS

    The numbers are just there for line references. IGNORE them. An example
    file would look like this:

      Internet Dockbar
      11

    This would mean that there would be 11 icons on the dock, and that the
    title of the dockbar would be 'Internet Dockbar'.
    Just edit this file in a normal text editor, like ED, and you will be
    away. JUST REMEMBER TO IGNORE THE LINE NUMBERS!!!!

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}program@{FG TEXT}

      1. PROGRAM NAME FOR ICON 1
      2. PATH TO EXECUTABLE FOR ICON 1
      3. PATH TO IMAGE FILE FOR ICON 1
      4. PROGRAM NAME FOR ICON 2
      5. PATH TO EXECUTABLE FOR ICON 2
      6. PATH TO IMAGE FILE FOR ICON 2
      7. PROGRAM NAME FOR ICON 3
      8. PATH TO EXECUTABLE FOR ICON 3
      9. PATH TO IMAGE FILE FOR ICON 3

    .... and so on, until ICON is the same as the number set in general.
    and then, the VERY LAST LINE is

      X. PATH TO SELECTED IMAGE FILE

    so an example file for a 5 icon dockbar would be:

      Miami                                   +-
      Miami:Miami                            -+   Icon 1
      NetDOCK2:Images/Default/Miami.iff       +-
      GENESiS                                 +-
      AmiTCP:Genesis                         -+   Icon 2
      NetDOCK2:Images/Default/AmiTCP.iff      +-
      YAM                                     +-
      YAM:YAM                                -+   Icon 3
      NetDOCK2:Images/Default/YAM.iff         +-
      Microdot II                             +-
      Internet:Microdot-II/Microdot          -+   Icon 4
      NetDOCK2:Images/Default/Microdot2.iff   +-
      AmFTP                                   +-
      NetConnect2:Programs/AmFTP/AmFTP       -+   Icon 5
      NetDOCK2:Images/Default/AmFTP.iff       +-
      NetDOCK2:Images/Default/Selected.iff   ---  Selected image file

    Ignore the comments on the side there.

    WHATEVER YOU DO, DO NOT PUT A SMALLER AMOUNT OF ICON DATA INTO THE
    program FILE THAN YOU DID IN THE general FILE, OTHERWISE THE PROGRAM
    WILL CRASH!!!!!!

  @{FG HIGHLIGHT}window@{FG TEXT}

    I may as well tell you the format of this file. Dead simple:

      1. X VALUE
      2. Y VALUE

    For example, the default values (0,14) would be:

      0
      14

    Again, IGNORE THE LINE NUMBERS!
@ENDNODE
